06297nam a22008415i 9780813542492DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20042004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135424927 a10.36019/97808135424922doi  a(DE-B1597)530277  a(OCoLC)804665128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a302.2322200aGlobal Currents :bMedia and Technology Now /ced. by Tasha G. Oren, Patrice Petro. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Directions in International Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI. Institutions: Nationalism, Transnationalism, Globalization -- tCrypto Regs — Fear, Greed, and the Destruction of the Digital Commons -- tWhat We Should Do and What We Should Forget in Media Studies — Or, My TV A–Z -- tHybridity -- t@henryparkesmotel.com -- tIs Television a Global Medium? — A Historical View -- tThe Land Grab for Bandwidth — Digital Conversion in an Era of Consolidation -- tPosthuman Law — Information Policy and the Machinic World -- tII. Circulation: Cultures, Strategies, Appropriations -- tPiracy, Infrastructure, and the Rise of a Nigerian Video Industry -- tUnsuitable Coverage — The Media, the Veil, and Regimes of Representation -- tMuscle, Market Value, Telegenesis, Cyberpresence — The New Asian Movie Star in the Global Economy of Masculine Images -- tThe African Diaspora Speaks in Digital Tongues -- tSome Versions of Difference — Discourses of Hybridity in Transnational Musics -- tAlternate Arrangement for Global Currents -- tNotes on contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRhetoric about media technology tends to fall into two extreme categories: unequivocal celebration or blanket condemnation. This is particularly true in debate over the clash of values when first world media infiltrate third world audiences. Bringing together the best new work on contemporary media practices, technologies, and policies, the essayists in Global Currents argue that neither of these extreme views accurately represents the role of media technology today. New ways of thinking about film, television, music, and the internet demonstrate that it is not only media technologies that affect the cultures into which they are introduced—it is just as likely that the receiving culture will change the media. Topics covered in the volume include copyright law and surveillance technology, cyber activism in the African Diaspora, transnational monopolies and local television industries, the marketing and consumption of “global music,” “click politics” and the war on Afghanistan, the techno-politics of distance education, artificial intelligence and global legal institutions, and traveling and “squatting” in digital space. Balanced between major theoretical positions and original field research, the selections address the political and cultural meanings that surround and configure new technologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBourdon, Jerome, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourdon, Jérôme, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraman, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCiecko, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverett, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFoner, Lenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarkin, Brian, eco